Content:


    In all other check points I have felt that they began from a very basic level.  This check point literally begins with, "As you may already know, GitHub is a platform that hosts code for version control and collaboration."

I am super excited to continue to get crappy, non specific, feedback that is expecting more out of me than I have been taught.  Thanks.

title: Student feedback for UNION checkpoint
body:
A student writes for this checkpoint https://courses.thinkful.com/dabc-sql-3-v1/checkpoint/3  

> 
> There are a couple questions actually. They're in module 15.3, items 5 and 8. The checkpoint covers UNIONS, which involves stacking 2 tables on top of each other, that have the same fields. The question asks for information which require a JOIN clause, which is another way to combine tables and was covered in the previous checkpoint. It asks for information from all customers, which in this database, are spread between 2 tables. So, to answer this question, you need to JOIN 2 tables, then use a UNION which was covered in this checkpoint to get all of the customer information. The problem is, the way to use a UNION and JOIN together was never covered, so I had to teach myself, which took a few hours and led to me giving up last night, because I couldn't get an exact match to any of the answers.
> When I discussed it with my mentor today, we ran the query with just the JOIN and not the UNION, and we got an output that matched one of the multiple choice questions. So, it seems that the second table with customer info in it was overlooked when the question was asked.
> It seems that both customer tables should be used when asking about all customer information, and how to do that should be covered in the checkpoint, or the question needs to be reworded.

Name: "Aggregation and calculated fields"

Course code: DABC-TABLEAU-1

Content:


    When the modal dialog for reporting typos and technical issues is accessed while the assignment container from Learnosity is active, the content of the active tab has a z-index of ten (the applet uses z-index and visibility styles to dynamically serve preloaded content) and the text of that active tab displays over the content of the model dialog.

Here's the id for the offending div:
#learnosity_assess_tableau-aggregation-calculations_Tab-54-Tab-16-Tab-17-Tab-18-Tab-19-Tab-20-Tab-62

I doubt much can be done about changing the vendor's applet, but if Thinkful devs could just set the z-index of .modal to 11, that should immediately resolve the conflict.

Consider revising the wording of this question.

title: Student feedback for UNION checkpoint
body:
A student writes for this checkpoint https://courses.thinkful.com/dabc-sql-3-v1/checkpoint/3  

> 
> There are a couple questions actually. They're in module 15.3, items 5 and 8. The checkpoint covers UNIONS, which involves stacking 2 tables on top of each other, that have the same fields. The question asks for information which require a JOIN clause, which is another way to combine tables and was covered in the previous checkpoint. It asks for information from all customers, which in this database, are spread between 2 tables. So, to answer this question, you need to JOIN 2 tables, then use a UNION which was covered in this checkpoint to get all of the customer information. The problem is, the way to use a UNION and JOIN together was never covered, so I had to teach myself, which took a few hours and led to me giving up last night, because I couldn't get an exact match to any of the answers.
> When I discussed it with my mentor today, we ran the query with just the JOIN and not the UNION, and we got an output that matched one of the multiple choice questions. So, it seems that the second table with customer info in it was overlooked when the question was asked.
> It seems that both customer tables should be used when asking about all customer information, and how to do that should be covered in the checkpoint, or the question needs to be reworded.

Consider revising the wording of this question.

title: [pgAdmin install questions]  Question from the Editing Team
body:
In the "SQL and the data analyst's toolbox" checkpoint, my editor had two related questions:

1. Right after walking the student through PostgreSQL and pgAdmin installation, the checkpoint sends the student back to the original install link. As far as I can tell, it's suggesting to immediately install it again to update. I might be misunderstanding. But there's also another link to this same page in the next section. Is it okay to remove the following quoted text and screenshot? 

"You now have both PostgreSQL and pgAdmin on your machine. You can also upgrade to the newest version of pgAdmin.  Go back to the [install page] (https://www.enterprisedb.com/downloads/postgres-postgresql-downloads), select the desired new version, and follow the download steps. This time, you will see the message below."

2. Related to the question above: should the following note stay? I'm wondering if it might be tricky to keep the gif updated whenpgAdmin releases new versions. 

"If your pgAdmin interface does not look like the screenshots below, you may be running an earlier version. If that is the case, you can download the latest version here."

title: [Redo assignment for more realistic]  User-submitted feedback for DABC-EXCEL-FOUNDATIONS-3
body:
Jeremiah Taylor (ophidian51@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Summarizing data"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/dabc-excel-foundations-3-v1/checkpoint/1

Course code: DABC-EXCEL-FOUNDATIONS-3

Content:


    First, I'd like to say that this is a great lesson.  The item descriptions very much represent how the data may come in the real world, incomplete, sometimes duplicate, sometimes nothing at all.  Took me right back to my retail management days with PetSmart.  However, the solution has us eliminating duplicate entries by the item description.  This is a problem because it eliminated some items that had the same description, but different stock codes.  This causes shrink, which is store loss, and all retail stores put a TON of effort into avoiding this.  My solution was to pull the item descriptions and stock code columns to the new table, select both, and eliminate the duplicates by the stock codes only.  I did have my mentor, Robert McKee check my work and he said everything looked great.  However this did give me different totals from what the answer provided.

title: [Checking data quality]  Question from the Editing Team
body:
In the "Checking data quality and adding calculations" checkpoint, my editor had this question:

"In the INDEX/MATCH formula, you'll notice that A1:I4 is always locked."

This description matches the formula in the screencast but not the workbook itself. In the workbook that's linked at the start of the checkpoint, it's A21:A24 that is locked (and A1:I4 just has introductory text). The checkpoint says to enter 

`=IF(G2>H2, MIN(G2-H2, I2-H2)*INDEX('2018_commission_structure'!$A$1:$I$4,MATCH($D2, '2018_commission_structure'!$A$1:$A$4, 0),MATCH(O$1, '2018_commission_structure'!$A$1:$I$1, 0)), 0)`

 into cell O2 of the Calculations tab, but the correct formula that's in the workbook is

`=IF($G2>H2,MIN($G2-H2,I2-H2)*INDEX('2018_commission_structure'!$A$21:$I$24,MATCH($D2,'2018_commission_structure'!$A$21:$A$24,0), MATCH(O$1,'2018_commission_structure'!$A$21:$I$21,0)),0)`. 

There are several formulas and screencasts with this same A1:A4 issue. Any thoughts?

title: Student feedback on Excel Foundations IV assignments
body:
An ASM forwarded me from student the below. These are the assignments for Excel IV where they are to build a profitability model. Each checkpoint builds on the previous. There is some confusion I think on what they are supposed to be doing as it relates to how the assignments progress.

You are welcome to tweak or revise the assignments or the instructions as you see fit.

>Greetings, some feedback from a student, “Hi Linnea,
I’m working on Module 8, and there’s 2 ongoing projects at the same time. One of them was asking to help a friend set up a spreadsheet to track and potentially maximize profitability. It asks you to list potential points of data and questions that might help you build the spreadsheet, then says to start it. I thought this was a project to create your own spreadsheet, so I spent a few hours putting it together before advancing. When I got to the most recent checkpoint I just finished, it then gave me data and told me to project out different strategies based on a spreadsheet that was already created. This left the spreadsheet that I designed by scratch worthless as far as the assignment is concerned.
I don’t necessarily feel like the work I put into what I believed to be the assignment was wasted, because I created something from scratch that was great practice, but it was very unclear what was going on. I just wanted to give a little feedback, since I couldn’t after I submitted the assignment and finished the checkpoint.
Again, this isn’t really a complaint, because I got some great practice out of it, but I was kind of lost on what to do.”

SELECT owners.pet_id,date
FROM owners FULL OUTER JOIN transactions ON owners.pet_id=transactions.pet_id
UNION
SELECT owners_2.pet_id,date
FROM owners_2 FULL OUTER JOIN transactions ON owners_2.pet_id=transactions.pet_id
WHERE date NOT BETWEEN '2019-06-16' AND '2019-06-22'
ORDER BY pet_id;

title: [Change the SQL ordering] Question from the Editing Team
body:
In the "HAVING and clause ordering" checkpoint (but also across SQL checkpoints), my editor had this question: 

I'm just looking at the table that orders the SQL clauses, and I was wondering about that order. This isn't critical, but we could reorder them to perhaps make it make more sense for the student.

Here's a quick summary: In SQL code, the clauses have to be written in the order S-F-W-G-H-O-L. The students learn the clauses in the order S-F-W-O-L-G-H. And the clause table that appears six times across six checkpoints is in the order S-F-W-O-G-H-L. I suggest reorganizing the clause table so that it matches either the SQL order or the order in which the students learn each clause.

My recommendation is to reorder the clause table to S-F-W-G-H-O-L so that it helps reinforce the order that the students need to memorize anyway. In the `HAVING` checkpoint, a couple sentences that describe the wrong table order would need to be adjusted. Everything else could stay the same.
